The paper deals with multi-agent systems and game theory, which are both subfields of computer science. The focus on coordination and resource allocation suggests that the paper belongs to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. The use of learning algorithms and the mention of "smart" and "stupid" agents suggest that the paper also belongs to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) and Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The use of multiple agents and the mention of a multi-agent learning algorithm suggest that the paper also belongs to the Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-category. Finally, the mention of a channel allocation game suggests that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category.
